The paper discusses algorithms for computing the LZ factorization of a string, which is a fundamental problem in data compression, text indexing, and pattern discovery. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.IT (information theory), cs.CC (computational complexity), cs.DC (distributed, parallel, and cluster computing), and cs.SI (social and information networks). Among these, cs.DS is the most likely category, as the paper focuses on developing new algorithms for a specific data structure problem. cs.IT is also a likely category, as the paper discusses the theoretical properties of the algorithms in terms of their space and time complexity. cs.CC and cs.DC are less likely categories, as the paper does not explicitly address issues related to parallel or distributed computing. cs.SI is also a less likely category, as the paper does not focus on social or network-related applications of the LZ factorization.
